116
00:06:51,675 --> 00:06:55,255
We have an incredible network
around the world,

117
00:06:55,255 --> 00:06:58,065
but what is the content 
that people need to know

118
00:06:58,065 --> 00:07:03,084
at a time when knowing
the right answer to some questions

119
00:07:03,084 --> 00:07:05,656
can be the difference 
between life and death.

120
00:07:05,656 --> 00:07:08,117
Is there an alternative to social media?

121
00:07:08,117 --> 00:07:09,885
That's a very interesting question.

122
00:07:09,885 --> 00:07:12,878
We always try to answer in one way.

123
00:07:12,878 --> 00:07:15,078
Whatever works in the field.

124
00:07:15,078 --> 00:07:17,959
First and foremost,
I think we should not assume

125
00:07:17,959 --> 00:07:20,249
that we understand how people communicate

126
00:07:20,249 --> 00:07:22,949
and what questions
they are looking answers for.

127
00:07:22,949 --> 00:07:27,068
The most important thing is to go
to the source, to the experts

128
00:07:27,068 --> 00:07:29,759
and figure out what works for them
and what doesn't work for them.

129
00:07:29,759 --> 00:07:32,048
And there's not going 
to be a silver bullet.

130
00:07:32,048 --> 00:07:33,768
There's not going to be a "killer app",

131
00:07:33,768 --> 00:07:35,884
there's not going to be
one solution that fits all.

132
00:07:35,884 --> 00:07:38,478
There's always going to be 
a multi-platform, multi-tiered approach

133
00:07:38,478 --> 00:07:42,500
that enables communities 
to communicate and reconnect from within,

134
00:07:42,500 --> 00:07:45,051
to communicate
with humanitarian responders

135
00:07:45,051 --> 00:07:48,049
and try to figure out what are
the best solutions.

136
00:07:48,423 --> 00:07:51,163
Alternatives to social media--
I think we've seen there's nothing

137
00:07:51,163 --> 00:07:54,151
that can replace face-to-face
human interaction.

138
00:07:54,471 --> 00:07:57,111
The question is in many emergencies
around the world--

139
00:07:57,111 --> 00:07:59,752
and this is less of an issue
in natural disasters--

140
00:07:59,972 --> 00:08:03,191
when we are talking about
armed conflicts, face-to-face

141
00:08:03,191 --> 00:08:07,402
it can become a luxury
because of security,

142
00:08:07,523 --> 00:08:10,823
because of a many number
of issues with regard to access

143
00:08:10,823 --> 00:08:13,162
doesn't enable us to spend
as much time as we would like

144
00:08:13,162 --> 00:08:17,093
to be in close proximity
with disaster efforts

145
00:08:17,093 --> 00:08:18,292
in communities.

146
00:08:18,292 --> 00:08:25,783
So the question is how we can also
build proximity 2.0

147
00:08:25,783 --> 00:08:28,274
using whatever technology may work.

148
00:08:28,274 --> 00:08:31,462
